    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-04-05T07:41:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-04-05T07:41:00-05:00" n="472"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d472">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">611.5631/188: Telegram (part air)</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in the Netherlands</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Wilson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">The Hague</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-04-05T13:00:00+00:19"
                            >April 5, 1935—1 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received April 6—7:47 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>27. Department’s telegram No. 13, April 4, 8 p.m. I have just had satisfactory
                    talk with Lamping. Legation in Washington had confused them and caused some
                    resentment. I believe they now appreciate difference between original plan and
                    the President’s letter to Secretary of the Treasury extending privileges pending
                    negotiations.</p>
                <p>I was surprised to see that Van Breugel had claimed that the Netherlands was not
                    discriminating against American commerce. They admit frankly here that the quota
                    and monopoly systems are discriminatory in their application if not in
                    principle. Lamping says Van Breugel was not instructed to make any such
                    statement.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Wilson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
